<title>
GC-biased evolution near human accelerated regions.
</title>

<text>

<sections.0>
Introduction
nderstanding the forces that have shaped the evolution of the human genome is one of the most exciting problems in modern genomics. wo approaches to this problem are focused on identification and characterization of those genomic regions that have evolved the slowest and fastest along the human lineage [1]β€“[5]. he slowest evolving regions may contain elements that cannot be disturbed without disrupting essential function. he fastest evolving regions may harbor elements whose function is unique to our species lineage. o eliminate non-functional regions, both of these complementary approaches begin with a search for regions that are conserved throughout mammalian history or longer. he ultra conserved elements [1] maintain this conservation along the human lineage, and have been shown to be under purifying (negative) selection [6], strongly suggesting that they are functionally important to our species, although in ways that are still largely unknown.
y contrast, several groups have searched for positive selection along the human lineage by focusing on those previously slowly evolving regions of the genome that have evolved most quickly along the human lineage [4], [5], [7]. hese regions, such as those in the set of uman ccelerated egions (s) [7], may include some of the genetic changes that make our species biologically unique. ndeed, biological characterization of the topmost elements on this list of candidates has proven fruitful: 1 is part of a novel  gene (1) that is expressed during neocortical development [3]; 2 (or 1) is a conserved non-coding sequence that has been shown to function as an enhancer in the developing limb bud with the human-specific sequence enhancing expression in the presumptive anterior wrist and proximal thumb [8].
ince the s were identified based on an excess of fixed differences between the human reference genome and sequences that are highly conserved among chimp, mouse and rat, such differences could have arisen at any time within the 5 million years that have elapsed since our common ancestor with the chimpanzee. s such it is important to recognize that even if such differences resulted from positive selection for advantageous mutations, they may have occurred so long ago that we have little power to find evidence for such selection using only the present day sequences available to us.
urthermore, as previously noted [7], positive selection might not be the sole explanation for the rapid evolution that is evident in the s. iased gene conversion () may also hasten the fixation of mutations in a local manner independent of any fitness benefits [9], [10].  arises as a byproduct of recombination between homologous chromosomal regions. n this process  double stranded breaks are repaired and the alleles from one chromosome are copied to the other, with a bias for conversion of  or  (weak hydrogen bonding) alleles to  or  (strong hydrogen bonding) alleles [11]β€“[14].  neutral locus can thus mimic the rapid evolution of loci under positive selection [9], [10], and furthermore,  may in fact drive fixation of deleterious alleles [15], the precise opposite of a positive, adaptive evolutionary effect.
ne of the most powerful tools for identifying those regions that have been subjected to directional selection comes from examining the distribution of allele frequencies segregating within a species. or example, analysis of this distribution, known as the site frequency spectrum (), allows for the identification of loci that have been involved in selective sweeps in the last few hundred thousand years. nalysis of the  has been used to identify targets of natural selection that may be responsible for genetic traits that are uniquely human, such as language [16] or cognition [17].
n the current work we investigate the top 49 s that were identified as having a 5% false discovery rate [3]. ut rather than restricting our attention to the core elements, which are 100β€“400bp in length, we consider the polymorphism in a set of 22 chromosomal human samples in a 40kb neighborhood of each of these  elements, with an eye to capturing perturbations in the  at linked sites, and/or regionally biased patterns of allele fixation. ur samples are drawn from a single population, the oruba from bidan, igeria in order to avoid confounding issues of population admixture as well as to take advantage of a greater degree of variation in this population. e use an adaptation of several techniques previously developed [18]β€“[21] to enrich genomic  from our sample individuals for the target genomic neighborhoods. he enriched  is then subject to high throughput sequencing followed by genome-wide mapping of many overlapping sequences to determine genotypes at sites in the target regions, and hence derive the site frequency spectra.
ith these spectra in hand, it is possible to test for the hallmarks of . e employed an approach that compares the separate site frequency spectra for the weak-to-strong (i.e.  or  to  or )(2) and strong-to-weak (2) mutations to determine if any shift towards high frequency, normally characteristic of a selective sweep, is biased towards one of the two sets of mutations. his signal would indicate an ongoing process in the current human population. imilarly, one can compare the proportion of 2 changes among already fixed substitutions on the human or chimp lineage to that among the still segregating sites.  2 bias in fixed differences relative to polymorphisms would indicate that the regions have historically been subject to a -like biased process.
n the other hand, the spectra may contain evidence of positive selection. arious techniques have emerged in recent years to search for signatures of positive selection using population genetic data [22]β€“[24], but many are based on the phenomenon of genetic hitchhiking [25], [26] in which fixation of beneficial mutations results in a skew in the site frequency spectrum. ne such approach [27] is based on the composite likelihood of allele frequencies wherein the probability of the observed allele frequency at each polymorphic position is calculated based on its distance from a site under putative positive selection. his probability explicitly takes into account the strength of recombination and selection.  variant of this approach has been implemented [28] in the weep. Finder program that we use herein. It has been previously used [29] in a genome-wide search for sweeps at the scale of 500kb, since that study's data was restricted to loci with common polymorphisms. The power of that approach is probably limited to finding sweeps not much older than 200,000 years but has the attractive property that it is robust to demographic history [29]. Unlike other approaches that have been used [22], [23], [30], [31] it also does not require that the sweep be ongoing or differentially concluded in separate populations. Since we have discovered many novel polymorphisms by resequencing our samples, we use this method to take a more focused look at our 40kb HAR neighborhoods in search of adaptive evolutionary forces.
