<sections.2>
Discussion
n the era of comparative genomics, strong signals of conservation across multiple species serve as signposts that can indicate regions where evolutionary forces may be preserving functional elements that are subject to purifying selection (e.g. [6]). y contrast, signals of positive selection pointing to adaptive changes in one lineage are harder to find, often employing sets of polymorphic sequences from multiple individuals of the same species. e exploited the two recently developed techniques of genomic enrichment and high throughput sequencing to characterize the polymorphism in a single human population across 40kb neighborhoods of the 49 s (harseq regions). e investigated the harseq regions because the s were defined based on a presumption that the human lineage specific fixed differences therein might have arisen due to adaptive evolutionary forces. n the other hand, it has been emphasized by some that the presumably evolutionarily neutral mechanism of  can influence the frequency spectra at polymorphic positions, or cause fixation of alleles in a way that partially mimics the action of adaptive evolution. ndeed, fixation bias was noted in connection with the limited set of human specific alleles for some of the s when they were first described [7].
ith the extensive novel polymorphism in our samples, we were able to carefully characterize fixation bias β€” both historical and ongoing β€” in the harseq regions and to conduct tests for recent selective sweeps across these regions. ur deep resequencing data is noteworthy because it eliminates issues of  ascertainment bias that could have skewed previous investigations of polymorphism near s. e applied several established population genetic tests, as well as an application of the  test, to identify differences in the fixation patterns of 2 and 2 mutations.
